  "text": "where p is the occupation probability and t is the critical exponent . The packing density defined as the ratio of the powder weight to the enclosure volume is adopted in this work as the independent variable describing percolation behavior instead of the volume/weight fraction due to the complex nature of the MUT . The critical exponent t is estimated theoretically to be between 1 . 6 and 2 for three dimensional percolation networks . However , experiments show that its value varies from 1 . 3 to 3 . 1 [CITATION_1] . For the studied CNTs , the critical exponent obtained by the linear regression fitting curve of the conductivity at 100 MHz shown in Fig . 5 is 2 . 6 which agrees with the percolation data reported in the literature . Fig. 3 : Extracted conductivity fu nction of the frequency of carbon nanotubes in a dry powder form using the measurement setups presented in Fig. I and Fig. 2 for different packing densities. The data obtained for densities below 0.4 g/cm 3 are obtained from the coaxial discontinuity setup while above this density statistical measurements variation are extracted from the transmission line measurement setup. At low frequencies the variation of the conductivity function of the density is higher as the wavelength of the electromagnetic are larger than the separation between two metallic particles . When the frequency range increases to the GHz range the conductivity decreases as the losses such as skin effect and semiconducting/conducting CNTs interconnect effects cannot be neglected anymore .",
